{
    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix resource cleanup in load_module_version_shlib function\n\n### Summary\nThe `load_module_version_shlib` function in the shared library loader was not properly cleaning up allocated resources on early returns or error paths. When loading a new shared library, if any error occurred after allocating resources for the library entry (name, path, function arrays), those resources were leaked and `loader_data.numshlibs` was not decremented.\n\nThis issue could lead to memory leaks and potentially cause the loader to incorrectly report that it has reached the maximum number of shared libraries when it had actually failed to load some libraries completely.\n\n### Changes\n- `common/utils/load_module_shlib.c`: Added proper cleanup of allocated resources on error paths when loading new libraries. This includes freeing library name, path, version strings, and function arrays. Also added initialization of all fields in new library entries and proper decrementing of `loader_data.numshlibs` on failure.\n- `common/utils/load_module_shlib.c`: Updated `loader_reset` function to also free `shlib_version` and `shlib_buildversion` fields for consistency.\n\n"
}